    <node id="1. Sian Gwenllian AM expressed sympathy with trying to tie down specific time periods for completing consultations and reports, but did not explicitly state her stance on amending the Bill to include them. She encouraged the Deputy Minister not to move her amendments if she received confirmation regarding these issues in the meeting.&#10;2. Suzy Davies AM, whose amendment proposals likely included specific time periods, seemed open to discussion and reaching an agreement, as indicated by her welcoming additional input to the Bill through amendment 2 and expressing willingness to listen to the Deputy Minister's suggestions.&#10;3. Lynne Neagle AM appeared neutral, focusing on facilitating the meeting and putting various amendments to a vote without expressing personal opinions or stances.&#10;4. Julie Morgan AM, the Deputy Minister for Health and Social Services, showed some resistance to making the commencement of the Bill conditional on revising Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) guidance or establishing a diversion pathway from the criminal justice system. However, she expressed willingness to discuss and find common ground regarding consultation and discussion methods before Stage 3 proceedings.&#10;&#10;In summary, Sian Gwenllian AM and Suzy Davies AM seem open to incorporating specific time periods for completing consultations and reports in the Bill, while Deputy Minister Julie Morgan AM has shown some resistance but is willing to discuss and find common ground. Lynne Neagle AM acts mainly as a facilitator without expressing personal opinions on the matter." />
    <node id=" Siân.&#10;Speaker: Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: Yes, I welcome adding to the Bill through amendment 2, and what you've said today also, that you're willing to provide an interim report and bring an amendment forward to allow that through the Bill, and to lay a report before the Assembly. I am interested in what Suzy is saying, and have a lot of sympathy with trying to tie it down to specific time periods, and not say 'when it will be practicable'. Therefore, I would encourage you not to move your amendments if you have the confirmation that you want to hear this morning from the Minister regarding these issues.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: I would like to. Thanks.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Thank you. Any other Members? No. Deputy Minister.&#10;Speaker: Julie Morgan AM&#10;Content: Well, just to start off on that point, I think your suggestion about how we consult and discuss, I think I'm very happy to accept that. So, I'm happy to discuss that with you, and with the committee, before the third Stage. So, I hope you will consider removing—.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies" />
    <node id="Based on the transcript, the Deputy Minister for Health and Social Services does not explicitly mention any measures she is willing to take to ensure that the awareness campaign for the implementation of a new criminal offense has no adverse impacts on those affected and does not delay the commencement date of the draft Bill. However, she does express her commitment to a public awareness campaign and agrees to consider Amendment 2B, which suggests some work being done around the amendment. The discussion gets interrupted at this point, and the Deputy Minister requests a private meeting with the committee, making it unclear what specific measures she proposed.&#10;&#10;It is also important to note that during the discussion, Suzy Davies AM mentions that Amendment 2C, which requests the Welsh Government prepare a report on the awareness-raising campaign before section 1 commences, should not affect or jeopardize the commencement date. She notes that failing to meet the operational requirement for this report would be due to operations not going well rather than anything intrinsic in the amendment itself.&#10;&#10;In summary, while there is no direct information about specific measures the Deputy Minister is willing to take as stated in the question, she does express her commitment to a public awareness campaign and agrees to consider Amendment 2B. The discussion around Amendment 2C implies that there should be no delays in the commencement date due to this report requirement." />
    <node id="1. The Welsh Government plans to implement a duty to provide information on alternatives to physical punishment. This would ensure that future Welsh Governments continue to make harder-to-reach groups and parents without internet access aware of the changes to the law and available support.&#10;2. They also aim to work with organizations to establish robust methods for capturing meaningful data relating to the Bill, which will help identify and address any gaps in reaching these groups.&#10;3. The Welsh Government is committed to conducting attitudinal surveys to track changes in attitude towards physical punishment of children and prevalence of parents reporting that they use physical punishment. These surveys will assist in monitoring the effectiveness of their awareness-raising campaign, ensuring it reaches all segments of society.&#10;4. A task and finish group has been set up to work with organizations and put in place arrangements for capturing data related to the Bill's impact on services. This will help identify any potential challenges or areas that require additional focus in reaching harder-to-reach groups and parents without internet access.&#10;5. The Welsh Government is preparing to assess the effectiveness of their awareness raising, which includes ensuring sufficient time is available prior to the change in the law for parents to understand the new legal framework and available alternatives to physical punishment." />
    <node id=" work hard to ensure that harder-to-reach groups receive this information, a duty to provide information on alternatives to physical punishment would ensure that future Welsh Governments would maintain a successful awareness-raising campaign. I note the Deputy Minister accepted the recommendation, through our amendment, but this does not explicitly include a duty to provide details about support for parents. As will be expanded upon later, the Deputy Minister has relied upon the 'Parenting: Give it Time' campaign to be delivered alongside awareness raising. However, this is only an online resource and she must be clear about what other avenues will be available to parents who do not have access to the internet or are part of harder-to-reach groups. Amendment 1C: amendment 1C supports the committee's recommendation 15 that explains that the Welsh Government should ensure clear advice is provided on what people can do if they have seen or learned of a child being physically assaulted. We urged, at Stage 1, that although many professionals were already under a duty to report concerns about physical punishment, regardless of the Bill, other witnesses raised concerns that it could create the potential for claims of abuse that are unfounded. In particular, some were worried that children, who may not realise the implications of reporting, could make allegations that are actually untrue. While" />
