    <node id="1. Including a duty on Welsh Ministers to promote public awareness and understanding about the effect of the Bill on the abolition of the defense of reasonable punishment is necessary because it ensures that future governments will continue the public awareness campaign, even if they have less commitment to doing so. While the Welsh Government intends to deliver a public awareness campaign, specific requirements in the Bill can provide reassurance to the Assembly about its involvement in designing the campaign and scrutinizing its effectiveness before section 1 commences.&#10;2. Specifying certain groups such as visitors to Wales or topics in the proposed awareness-raising campaign is not necessary or helpful. The Welsh Government's existing duties and commitment to children's rights, along with the government's intention to deliver a comprehensive public awareness campaign, should be sufficient. Additional specifications may risk placing too much emphasis on certain groups at the expense of others and unnecessarily limit the flexibility of the awareness-raising campaign.&#10;3. Adding an additional due regard requirement for promoting awareness among children through the legislation is not necessary because Welsh Ministers are already under a duty to have due regard to the rights of children whenever they exercise their functions, which includes promoting awareness among children as part of the Welsh Government approach to putting children’s rights at the heart of their policy making." />
    <node id=" of years. Therefore, an ongoing duty referring specifically to the law change would not be required. I understand, of course, that the awareness-raising campaign needs to be comprehensive, well planned and to reach out to all those people and all those communities who need to be aware of the law change, and understand how to respond to it. But I don't think it's helpful or necessary to highlight specific groups, such as visitors to Wales, on the face of the Bill—that's the approach taken in amendment 1E—as it risks placing too much emphasis on certain groups at the expense of others. In relation to children, the committee will know that I'm fully committed to children’s rights, and that Welsh Ministers are already under a duty to have due regard to the rights of children whenever they exercise their functions. An additional due regard requirement, such as the one set out in amendment 1D, relating specifically to the need to promote awareness among children is not needed. This would be part and parcel of the Welsh Government approach to putting children’s rights at the heart of our policy making. Similarly, I don't think it's necessary for the Bill to set out specifically the topics that need to be covered in the awareness-raising campaign, as is" />
    <node id="The disagreement over the duration of the awareness campaign arises from a misunderstanding during the committee discussion. Suzy Davies AM seemed to have understood that the awareness campaign would last for two years, while Julie Morgan AM clarified that the planned duration for the awareness campaign is actually six years from the time of Royal Assent. The speaker, who is supporting the Bill, confirmed the six-year duration for the awareness campaign, which will commence once the Bill is passed and receive Royal Assent." />
