    <edge source="The disagreement between Suzy Davies AM and Julie Morgan AM regarding the duration of the awareness campaign is related to the implementation of the proposed Bill, which aims to remove the defense of reasonable punishment. Suzy Davies AM seemed to have understood that the awareness campaign would last for two years, while Julie Morgan AM clarified that the planned duration for the awareness campaign is actually six years from the time of Royal Assent. This clarification helped in confirming that the campaign would indeed continue beyond the point when section 1 of the Bill comes into force." target=" is as a result of the recommendation from this committee that we are putting this duty to have the awareness campaign on the face of the Bill, and I absolutely recognise the crucial role awareness raising has to play in supporting the implementation of the Bill. I'm very grateful for and appreciate the committee's interest and the work that you've done in this area of work. But I do think that these amendments are unnecessary. If we go through them, amendment 1A is really open-ended on promoting public awareness. We're committed to a high-intensity awareness over six years from Royal Assent, and there is an expert stakeholder group supporting us with the development of the awareness campaign. All the points that you've been making will be being considered by that group. I think the level of detail on the face of the Bill is not needed.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Okay. Would you just take an intervention on that just to help me understand? A two-year awareness-raising campaign—how have you concluded that—&#10;Speaker: Julie Morgan AM&#10;Content: Six-year.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: I thought it was two years before section 1 comes into force.&#10;Speaker: Julie Morgan AM">
