    <edge source="The disagreement between Suzy Davies AM and Julie Morgan AM regarding the duration of the awareness campaign is related to the implementation of the proposed Bill, which aims to remove the defense of reasonable punishment. Suzy Davies AM seemed to have understood that the awareness campaign would last for two years, while Julie Morgan AM clarified that the planned duration for the awareness campaign is actually six years from the time of Royal Assent. This clarification helped in confirming that the campaign would indeed continue beyond the point when section 1 of the Bill comes into force." target="1. Data Collection and Post-Implementation Review: The Welsh Government is working with organizations to collect data about the possible impact of the Bill on their services. This data will be analyzed as part of the post-implementation review of the legislation, which will not be a single piece of work but a continuous program of work during the years following the commencement of section 1. Attitudinal surveys will be conducted to track changes in attitude towards the physical punishment of children and prevalence of parents reporting that they use physical punishment.&#10;2. Awareness Campaign: The Welsh Government plans to conduct an awareness campaign for six years from the time of Royal Assent, which will continue beyond the point when section 1 of the Bill comes into force. This campaign aims to promote public awareness and understanding about the effect of the Bill on the abolition of the defense of reasonable punishment.&#10;3. Regulatory Impact Assessment (RIA): The Welsh Government has asked officials to prepare a revised RIA, which will include more detailed estimates of the unknown costs to public services arising from the Bill. They expect to share this updated RIA with relevant stakeholders in advance of Stage 3.&#10;4. Regulatory Powers: Consideration is being given to amending the Bill to include unrestricted power to make regulations, ensuring effective execution and proper scrutiny in the Welsh Assembly. This would help manage any potential impact on workloads, resources, and cost implications resulting from the removal of the longstanding defense to common assault offenses.&#10;5. Budget Scrutiny: The National Assembly for Wales scrutinizes the Welsh Government budget annually, allowing for arguments to be made for additional funding for public bodies if required. This process ensures that future governments can consider priorities within the context of the budget-setting process, taking into account any unforeseen impacts on the economy or Welsh society.">
