    <edge source=" is as a result of the recommendation from this committee that we are putting this duty to have the awareness campaign on the face of the Bill, and I absolutely recognise the crucial role awareness raising has to play in supporting the implementation of the Bill. I'm very grateful for and appreciate the committee's interest and the work that you've done in this area of work. But I do think that these amendments are unnecessary. If we go through them, amendment 1A is really open-ended on promoting public awareness. We're committed to a high-intensity awareness over six years from Royal Assent, and there is an expert stakeholder group supporting us with the development of the awareness campaign. All the points that you've been making will be being considered by that group. I think the level of detail on the face of the Bill is not needed.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Okay. Would you just take an intervention on that just to help me understand? A two-year awareness-raising campaign—how have you concluded that—&#10;Speaker: Julie Morgan AM&#10;Content: Six-year.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: I thought it was two years before section 1 comes into force.&#10;Speaker: Julie Morgan AM" target="1. The Welsh Government is not providing specific reassurances about the involvement of the Assembly in designing the public awareness-raising campaign if minimum requirements are not included on the face of the Bill. This is because, as Suzy Davies AM mentions, there is a lack of clarity on how the Welsh Government plans to involve the Assembly in creating the specifics of the public awareness campaign through regulations. The Assembly has concerns that, without having some of these requirements and guidelines included in the Bill itself, they may have little to no influence over the content and execution of the awareness-raising campaign.">
