    <edge source=" the last 20 years, and I'm not aware of any legislation where, on the face of the Bill we have ongoing awareness-raising campaigns on an indefinite basis. It seems to me that, for some reason, you seem to be wanting to take a completely different approach to this piece of legislation. From what the Deputy Minister is saying—and perhaps I will get some clarity on this—there will be an amendment to the legislation that will say that we have an awareness campaign. That awareness campaign can be the subject of consultation with interested parties in terms of what needs to be included in it. It could also, I assume, Deputy Minister, be an awareness campaign that can be written into a set of guidance for future use. But the point I'm trying to make is that I don't believe that any piece of legislation requires ongoing and indefinite awareness-raising campaigns, and particularly in relation to visitors to Wales. Again, we have other pieces of legislation in Wales that are not applicable in the other parts of the UK. I am not aware that there is a necessity for awareness-raising campaigns with visitors coming into Wales on the raft of the other pieces of legislation that we have that they don't. And similarly, when we go to visit countries that have different legislation, we" target="1. Including a duty on Welsh Ministers to promote public awareness and understanding about the effect of the Bill on the abolition of the defense of reasonable punishment is necessary because it ensures that future governments will continue the public awareness campaign, even if they have less commitment to doing so. While the Welsh Government intends to deliver a public awareness campaign, specific requirements in the Bill can provide reassurance to the Assembly about its involvement in designing the campaign and scrutinizing its effectiveness before section 1 commences.&#10;2. Specifying certain groups such as visitors to Wales or topics in the proposed awareness-raising campaign is not necessary or helpful. The Welsh Government's existing duties and commitment to children's rights, along with the government's intention to deliver a comprehensive public awareness campaign, should be sufficient. Additional specifications may risk placing too much emphasis on certain groups at the expense of others and unnecessarily limit the flexibility of the awareness-raising campaign.&#10;3. Adding an additional due regard requirement for promoting awareness among children through the legislation is not necessary because Welsh Ministers are already under a duty to have due regard to the rights of children whenever they exercise their functions, which includes promoting awareness among children as part of the Welsh Government approach to putting children’s rights at the heart of their policy making.">
