    <edge source="1. The proposed revised guidance for section 1 of the Children (Abolition of Defence of Reasonable Punishment) (Wales) Bill may not directly ensure natural justice and proportionate remedy or censure, as the guidance does not have legal power over how parents might be punished for smacking their children. The powers and duties of law enforcement and prosecution services are outside the competence of the Welsh Government.&#10;2. The Welsh Government acknowledges that revised CPS charging guidance and other guidance on out-of-court disposals are key to delivering their policy objectives. However, at the time of the meeting, the strategic implementation group was only in the early stages of discussing what these guidelines might look like.&#10;3. To devise and agree on pathways away from prosecution before bringing this section into force, amendments 10 and 15 have been tabled by Janet Finch-Saunders AM and Lynne Neagle AM. These amendments prevent the Welsh Government from bringing section 1 into force until CPS guidance has been fully updated to take into account the change in the law and until pathways away from prosecution have been devised and agreed. This reflects recommendation 4 of the committee, ensuring that future governments are committed to delivering a public awareness campaign and promoting understanding about the effect of the Bill on the abolition for the defence of reasonable punishment." target=" look like. So, you're actually asking us to pass law when we have no control over how parents might be punished for smacking their children—no control of the regard given to the relevance of force, the frequency of the offence, any prior conviction, any prior reporting, not even the views of the child in how they might be sentenced, or thresholds that would be appropriate for cautions and other out-of-court disposals; no guidance to the police on thresholds for arrest, let alone charging. And you argue that the rights of the child are what matter, and I agree with you here, but everybody, adult or child, has a right to natural justice and proportionate remedy or censure, and you are in no position to offer us any comfort on these matters at this stage. Now, CLAC recommended that any revised guidance be made available to AMs before Stage 3. I anticipate that that's unlikely, and I hope I'm wrong, but that's why Janet and I have tabled amendments 10 and 15, which prevent you bringing section 1 into force until that CPS guidance has been fully updated to take into account the change in the law and until pathways away from prosecution have been devised and agreed. That reflects our recommendation 4, this committee's">
