    <edge source="1. The proposed revised guidance for section 1 of the Children (Abolition of Defence of Reasonable Punishment) (Wales) Bill may not directly ensure natural justice and proportionate remedy or censure, as the guidance does not have legal power over how parents might be punished for smacking their children. The powers and duties of law enforcement and prosecution services are outside the competence of the Welsh Government.&#10;2. The Welsh Government acknowledges that revised CPS charging guidance and other guidance on out-of-court disposals are key to delivering their policy objectives. However, at the time of the meeting, the strategic implementation group was only in the early stages of discussing what these guidelines might look like.&#10;3. To devise and agree on pathways away from prosecution before bringing this section into force, amendments 10 and 15 have been tabled by Janet Finch-Saunders AM and Lynne Neagle AM. These amendments prevent the Welsh Government from bringing section 1 into force until CPS guidance has been fully updated to take into account the change in the law and until pathways away from prosecution have been devised and agreed. This reflects recommendation 4 of the committee, ensuring that future governments are committed to delivering a public awareness campaign and promoting understanding about the effect of the Bill on the abolition for the defence of reasonable punishment." target=" aware of many of those pieces of legislation. This particular piece of legislation will have a profound effect on the parenting of children in Wales. So, therefore, I think there is a necessity for both children and parents to become involved, and I shall speak now—&#10;Speaker: Dawn Bowden AM&#10;Content: With respect, Chair, that's not the question I asked.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: —to my amendments.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: I can call you in the debate, if you'd like to make a more substantive contribution on this. Yes.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: The witnesses who we heard from before this committee also noted the necessity of ensuring that the public understands the implications. And that's what we're talking about here, Members—the implications of removing this defence. Strikingly, the Office of Police and Crime Commissioner for Gwent stated the following: 'the potential for public resistance to the Bill through misunderstanding or confusion over it implications may pose the largest barrier to its implementation.' If you are intent on removing the defence of reasonable punishment, it is therefore not unreasonable to ensure that law-abiding parents fully understand the ramifications of this">
