    <edge source="1. The proposed revised guidance for section 1 of the Children (Abolition of Defence of Reasonable Punishment) (Wales) Bill may not directly ensure natural justice and proportionate remedy or censure, as the guidance does not have legal power over how parents might be punished for smacking their children. The powers and duties of law enforcement and prosecution services are outside the competence of the Welsh Government.&#10;2. The Welsh Government acknowledges that revised CPS charging guidance and other guidance on out-of-court disposals are key to delivering their policy objectives. However, at the time of the meeting, the strategic implementation group was only in the early stages of discussing what these guidelines might look like.&#10;3. To devise and agree on pathways away from prosecution before bringing this section into force, amendments 10 and 15 have been tabled by Janet Finch-Saunders AM and Lynne Neagle AM. These amendments prevent the Welsh Government from bringing section 1 into force until CPS guidance has been fully updated to take into account the change in the law and until pathways away from prosecution have been devised and agreed. This reflects recommendation 4 of the committee, ensuring that future governments are committed to delivering a public awareness campaign and promoting understanding about the effect of the Bill on the abolition for the defence of reasonable punishment." target="1. The defense to a criminal act being removed implies that parents who physically punish their children can be held liable for prosecution under the criminal law, even if they do not necessarily get prosecuted. This shift from civil enforcement to criminal law has implications for parents because it opens them up to criminal charges, which can have severe consequences such as fines or imprisonment.&#10;2. There is a concern about having no control over how parents might be punished for smacking their children despite aiming not to criminalize them because the powers and duties of law enforcement and prosecution services are outside the competence of the Welsh Government. This means that while the government acknowledges the need for revised CPS charging guidance and other guidelines to ensure a proportionate response, they cannot directly control or dictate how these bodies handle cases related to physical punishment.&#10;3. The proposed amendments (10 and 15) by Janet Finch-Saunders AM and Lynne Neagle AM aim to prevent the Welsh Government from bringing section 1 into force until CPS guidance has been fully updated and pathways away from prosecution have been devised and agreed, reflecting the committee's recommendation for a public awareness campaign promoting understanding about the effect of the Bill on the abolition of the defense of reasonable punishment. This would help ensure natural justice and proportionate remedy or censure, while being mindful of the relationship between parents and children in each family.">
