    <edge source="1. The Welsh Government plans to implement a duty to provide information on alternatives to physical punishment. This would ensure that future Welsh Governments continue to make harder-to-reach groups and parents without internet access aware of the changes to the law and available support.&#10;2. They also aim to work with organizations to establish robust methods for capturing meaningful data relating to the Bill, which will help identify and address any gaps in reaching these groups.&#10;3. The Welsh Government is committed to conducting attitudinal surveys to track changes in attitude towards physical punishment of children and prevalence of parents reporting that they use physical punishment. These surveys will assist in monitoring the effectiveness of their awareness-raising campaign, ensuring it reaches all segments of society.&#10;4. A task and finish group has been set up to work with organizations and put in place arrangements for capturing data related to the Bill's impact on services. This will help identify any potential challenges or areas that require additional focus in reaching harder-to-reach groups and parents without internet access.&#10;5. The Welsh Government is preparing to assess the effectiveness of their awareness raising, which includes ensuring sufficient time is available prior to the change in the law for parents to understand the new legal framework and available alternatives to physical punishment." target=" work hard to ensure that harder-to-reach groups receive this information, a duty to provide information on alternatives to physical punishment would ensure that future Welsh Governments would maintain a successful awareness-raising campaign. I note the Deputy Minister accepted the recommendation, through our amendment, but this does not explicitly include a duty to provide details about support for parents. As will be expanded upon later, the Deputy Minister has relied upon the 'Parenting: Give it Time' campaign 