    <edge source="1. The Welsh Government plans to implement a duty to provide information on alternatives to physical punishment. This would ensure that future Welsh Governments continue to make harder-to-reach groups and parents without internet access aware of the changes to the law and available support.&#10;2. They also aim to work with organizations to establish robust methods for capturing meaningful data relating to the Bill, which will help identify and address any gaps in reaching these groups.&#10;3. The Welsh Government is committed to conducting attitudinal surveys to track changes in attitude towards physical punishment of children and prevalence of parents reporting that they use physical punishment. These surveys will assist in monitoring the effectiveness of their awareness-raising campaign, ensuring it reaches all segments of society.&#10;4. A task and finish group has been set up to work with organizations and put in place arrangements for capturing data related to the Bill's impact on services. This will help identify any potential challenges or areas that require additional focus in reaching harder-to-reach groups and parents without internet access.&#10;5. The Welsh Government is preparing to assess the effectiveness of their awareness raising, which includes ensuring sufficient time is available prior to the change in the law for parents to understand the new legal framework and available alternatives to physical punishment." target=" No. I'd rather crack on, to be honest.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Okay. I can call you in the debate, Hefin.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: Should our amendment to be agreed, we also request that a printing change be made to ensure that the new heading reflects promoting awareness of the changes to the law made by section 1. Amendment 1B: amendment 1B is in line with the committee's recommendation 9, which stated that, as part of a public awareness campaign, there should be details about the support available to parents to use alternatives to physical punishment when disciplining their children. During evidence at Stage 1, the witnesses we saw before the committee raised serious concerns about harder-to-reach groups who needed to be made aware of removing the defence. For example, Children in Wales, Action for Children and Play Wales stated that some families and communities may be harder to reach with information and support. Welsh Government needs to make sure that they receive the information they need. Now, while the Deputy Minister states that she would work hard to ensure that harder-to-reach groups receive this information, a duty to provide information on alternatives to physical punishment would ensure that future Welsh Governments would">
