    <edge source="1. Including a duty on Welsh Ministers to promote public awareness and understanding about the effect of the Bill on the abolition of the defense of reasonable punishment is necessary because it ensures that future governments will continue the public awareness campaign, even if they have less commitment to doing so. While the Welsh Government intends to deliver a public awareness campaign, specific requirements in the Bill can provide reassurance to the Assembly about its involvement in designing the campaign and scrutinizing its effectiveness before section 1 commences.&#10;2. Specifying certain groups such as visitors to Wales or topics in the proposed awareness-raising campaign is not necessary or helpful. The Welsh Government's existing duties and commitment to children's rights, along with the government's intention to deliver a comprehensive public awareness campaign, should be sufficient. Additional specifications may risk placing too much emphasis on certain groups at the expense of others and unnecessarily limit the flexibility of the awareness-raising campaign.&#10;3. Adding an additional due regard requirement for promoting awareness among children through the legislation is not necessary because Welsh Ministers are already under a duty to have due regard to the rights of children whenever they exercise their functions, which includes promoting awareness among children as part of the Welsh Government approach to putting children’s rights at the heart of their policy making." target=" of years. Therefore, an ongoing duty referring specifically to the law change would not be required. I understand, of course, that the awareness-raising campaign needs to be comprehensive, well planned and to reach out to all those people and all those communities who need to be aware of the law change, and understand how to respond to it. But I don't think it's helpful or necessary to highlight specific groups, such as visitors to Wales, on the face of the Bill—that's the approach taken in amendment 1E—as it risks placing too much emphasis on certain groups at the expense of others. In relation to children, the committee will know that I'm fully committed to children’s rights, and that Welsh Ministers are already under a duty to have due regard to the rights of children whenever they exercise their functions. An additional due regard requirement, such as the one set out in amendment 1D, relating specifically to the need to promote awareness among children is not needed. This would be part and parcel of the Welsh Government approach to putting children’s rights at the heart of our policy making. Similarly, I don't think it's necessary for the Bill to set out specifically the topics that need to be covered in the awareness-raising campaign, as is">
      <data key="d0">1</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="1. Including a duty on Welsh Ministers to promote public awareness and understanding about the effect of the Bill on the abolition of the defense of reasonable punishment is necessary because it ensures that future governments will continue the public awareness campaign, even if they have less commitment to doing so. While the Welsh Government intends to deliver a public awareness campaign, specific requirements in the Bill can provide reassurance to the Assembly about its involvement in designing the campaign and scrutinizing its effectiveness before section 1 commences.&#10;2. Specifying certain groups such as visitors to Wales or topics in the proposed awareness-raising campaign is not necessary or helpful. The Welsh Government's existing duties and commitment to children's rights, along with the government's intention to deliver a comprehensive public awareness campaign, should be sufficient. Additional specifications may risk placing too much emphasis on certain groups at the expense of others and unnecessarily limit the flexibility of the awareness-raising campaign.&#10;3. Adding an additional due regard requirement for promoting awareness among children through the legislation is not necessary because Welsh Ministers are already under a duty to have due regard to the rights of children whenever they exercise their functions, which includes promoting awareness among children as part of the Welsh Government approach to putting children’s rights at the heart of their policy making." target="1. The Welsh Government has deviated from the Scottish approach of requiring the promotion of public awareness and understanding about the effect of abolishing the defense of reasonable punishment in their amendment to remove the defense of reasonable punishment from the Children (Abolition of Defence of Reasonable Punishment) (Wales) Bill because they may have different perspectives on the necessity or effectiveness of such a provision. The Welsh Government might believe that their intentions to deliver a public awareness campaign are sufficient, and that specific requirements in the Bill could limit flexibility or unnecessarily focus on certain groups at the expense of others. Additionally, the Welsh Government's amendment may have been focused on other aspects of the Bill, and including this provision was not a priority for them at the time.">
